observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the –
 Municipal Accountant submit proof that the amount of ₱2,206.20 was utilized for the additional work of the project. Otherwise, together with the Municipal Treasurer, revert the said unexpended balance to the Bureau of Treasury;
 The Municipal Accountant –
 Furnish the Audit Team a copy of the FUR for DILG– LGSF 2019 (₱8,000,000.00) duly received by DILG/source agency;
 For the fund transfers from DA (₱1,071,000.00) and DOLE (₱508,000.00), prepare respective FURs and submit to the source agencies for their information. Copy of the duly received FURs be furnished to the Audit Team for verification;
 Determine the nature of fund deposited in the KALAHI account and accounting entries made thereto. Review and determine correctness of the accounting entries made for the MLGU counterpart charges totaling ₱253,410.00 (₱173,350.00 CY 2021 plus ₱80,060.00 CY 2022), and prepare necessary adjusting entries;
 Analyze and trace back the nature and composition of the balance ₱2,112,073.77, and subsequently prepare FUR/ROD or necessary adjustments, as appropriate; and
 Henceforth, prepare FUR or ROD in compliance with covering MOA or regulatory issuances, and submit the same to Source Agency for their information and reference.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
 Draw adjusting entries for the lapses noted to correct account balances;
 Look into the discrepancies noted in the remittances under GF (Table 5), and cause the remittance and or prepare necessary adjustment;
 Submit a certified true copy of the DV of the accrual for SEF, for verification;
 Analyze further balances of Due to BIR account under the General Fund (abnormal balance of ₱126,576.74, Table 5) and Trust Fund (₱124,359.14 of unknown nature, Table 9) and subsequently effect necessary adjustments to bring the correct balances; and
 Coordinate with the BIR for the possible offsetting of double remittances under the 20% DF (Table 6.1).

We recommended that the:
 Municipal Social Welfare and Development Officer (MSWDO) in coordination with the Municipal Accountant submit the lacking documents and see to it that the Acknowledgment Receipt be properly signed by the beneficiaries;
 For similar program in the future, the MSWDO develop strategies and ensure that before payout, Master List of Beneficiaries be carefully reviewed to eliminate possible duplication of names that could result in double payments; and the required supporting documents be properly check to ensure completeness and or avoid duplication thereof.

We recommended that Management:
 Cause the immediate transfer of ₱2,539,525.98 to GF so that the same can be utilize for other essential programs, projects and activities;
 Re-appropriate the savings from completed projects to other desirable development projects;
 Implement the development projects programmed during the year as embodied in the Municipal Development Plan (MDP) and ensure realistic planning and optimum utilization of the 20% Development Fund, in compliance with the provisions of DBM-DOF-DILG Joint Memorandum Circular 2020-1 and;
 Develop strategies so that all the development projects identified in the Municipal Development Plan are implemented or have at least started during the year for the attainment of desirable socio-economic targets of the MLGU.

We recommended that -
 Instruct the Department Heads or requesting office to make sure that their succeeding claims or Disbursement Vouchers (DV) are properly documented before submitting it to the Budget Office and Accounting Office for processing;
 Municipal Accountant provide checklist of documentary requirements for every DV and see to that the required supporting papers are attached to the DV before processing; if attachments are lacking or not properly accomplished, return the DV to the requesting office for completion. Attending payment of claims that are not sufficiently documented be discontinued; and Payment of Infrastructure Projects

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
 Draw the journal entry vouchers to close the CIP accounts to their proper completed asset accounts as well as to adjust the erroneously posted refunds of bid security and unutilized fund transfer, to correct balances of the accounts;
 Maintain subsidiary ledger per CIP account per project under each fund to provide complete information on the account and to support balances in the Financial Statements.

That management prepare the Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund Investment Plan (LDRRMFIP) in support to the purpose for which the fund was set aside and follow said plan accordingly;

The Obligation Request (ObR) attached to the vouchers should clearly indicate the cost center or funding source of the disbursement so as to serve as a control mechanism to ensure that funds are used for the intended purpose and appropriations are not exceeded as well as to facilitate preparation of accurate reports; and

Utilization of the 70% Pre Disaster and Mitigation and 30% Quick Response Fund should be in accordance with the Implementing Rules and Regulations of Republic Act No. 10121.

That management justify the above noted lapses. Henceforth, ensure that the utilization of the 20% Development Fund be limited to PPAs that partake the nature of investment or capital expenditures in accordance with DBM-DILG Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2011-1;
Ensure immediate submission of the noted un-submitted vouchers together with the lacking supporting documents for audit. Henceforth, ensure that the Municipal Accountant certify on disbursement vouchers only when all the necessary documents are attached. Likewise, that the Municipal Treasurer effect payments only on vouchers that are completely documented;
That the municipality utilize the unexpended balance for the intended purposes after due evaluation whether these are still priority concerns taking into consideration current developments and to accordingly re-appropriate the funds of PPAs that have become irrelevant or not responsive to current priority undertakings; and
Ensure regular transfer of the amount pertaining to the 20% Development Fund to its respective bank account so as to increase efficiency in the monitoring of the allocation and utilization of the fund.

That Management create an Inventory Committee that will perform the conduct of complete annual physical count of PPE in accordance with Section 124 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Vol. 1.  A representative of the Auditor be invited to witness the inventory taking for this purpose;
That the Property and Accounting Units maintain complete and accurate PPELC for each category of PPE pursuant to Section 114 on the NGAS Manual for LGUs in order to promote effective monitoring and controls over PPE;
That a reconciliation of the Property and Accounting records be done after the conduct of physical count;
That the Inventory Committee submit the Physical Inventory Reports to the Property Officer and COA Office for verification and reconciliation of the result of the physical inventory with the complete Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards and the Property Cards maintained by the Property and Accounting Units;
That the ARE/PAR be maintained and renewed every three years in accordance with the Instructions on the use of ARE/PAR; and
That the Property and Accounting Units comply with the prescribed procedures in COA Circular No. 89-296 on the disposal of unserviceable PPE, if any.

The Municipal Engineer and the Property Custodian conduct a yearly physical count of local road network projects and consequently update the local road map of the LGU;
The Municipal Engineer provide the Municipal Accountant and Property Custodian the description and cost segregation of road components of various road infrastructure projects; and
The Municipal Accountant keeps and maintain subsidiary ledger for roads and its components and reconcile the same to the result of the physical inventory taking at the end of each year.

That adherence to the rules on reception and entertainment of Official Visitors as prescribed by Section 343 of RA 7160 be strictly observed;
Furnish the abovementioned un-submitted vouchers and make the necessary adjustments for the erroneous entry; and
Submit SB Resolution authorizing the re-alignment of MOOE and/or the duly approved Ordinance providing for a Supplemental Budget for the additional appropriations for Representation Expenses.  Henceforth, limit the Utilization of funds within the budget/appropriations.

Thorough   evaluation of bids should be conducted by the Bids and Awards Committee.  Consider the disqualification of a bidder fails to submit the required financial and technical documents;
Publish in the PhilGEPs website all Invitation to bid/Request for Expression of and advertise in a newspaper of nationwide circulation all procurement costing ₱5 million and above;
Require the BAC members to attend trainings on RA 9184 to familiarize themselves of the provisions of the law; and
Invite observers in all stages of procurement.

That management submit written justification for the payments of infrastructures without the indispensable attachments;
That management submit the lacking documents for evaluation and review; and
Henceforth, the Municipal Accountant see to it that all disbursement vouchers are properly supported with complete documentation before any payment is made.

the Sanggunian Bayan to pass a resolution authorizing the Municipal Mayor and the Municipal Treasurer to open a separate bank account for the unexpended balance of LDRRMF;
the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to transfer the unexpended/unobligated balance of the LDRRMF to the Trust Fund to be opened; and
the Municipal Accountant to maintain a special account and a complete set of subsidiary for the said fund in accordance with the above stated provisions.

That the Management create an Inventory Committee that will perform the conduct of complete annual physical count of PPE in accordance with Section 124 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Vol. 1.  A representative of the Auditor be invited to witness the inventory taking for this purpose;
That the Property and Accounting Units maintain complete and accurate PPELC for each category of PPE pursuant to Section 114 on the NGAS Manual for LGUs in order to promote effective monitoring and controls over PPE;
That a reconciliation of the Property and Accounting records be done after the conduct of physical count;
That the Inventory Committee submit the Physical Inventory Reports to the Property Officer and COA Office for verification and reconciliation of the result of the physical inventory with the complete Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards and the Property Cards maintained by the Property and Accounting Units;
That the ARE/PAR be maintained and renewed every three years in accordance with the Instructions on the use of ARE/PAR; and
That the Property and Accounting Units comply with the prescribed procedures in COA Circular No. 89-296 on the disposal of unserviceable PPE, if any.

That expenses for the reception of visitors be charged to the Official’s Representation Allowance (RA). Adherence to the rules on reception and entertainment as prescribed by Section 343 of RA 7160 should be observed;
Furnish the abovementioned vouchers and make the necessary adjustments for the erroneous entry to account; and
Utilize funds within the budget/appropriations.

That the agency integrate in its budgeting an amount equal to 5% of the total appropriation for PPAs that address gender issues;

That a Gender and Development Plan be prepared containing the specific projects and activities addressing gender and development and equity for women and the utilization should be in accordance with the GAD Plan;

Ensure that Obligation Requests (OBRs) be duly accomplished and required registries of allotment and obligations are maintained; and

 Ensure that Accomplishment Reports contain the actual accomplishment vis-à-vis targets as well as the amounts utilized and a list of expenditures that are related with the utilization of the said fund.

We have recommended the following:
a. The Municipal Accountant should exert more effort to establish and determine nature of the accounts. Measures which include sending demand letters to debtors reminding them of their overdue obligations should be made;
b. If the receivables would be found uncollectible and unrecoverable, it should be written-off subject to the rules and regulations of the COA. The request for authority to write-off the accounts outstanding for more than 10 years should be forwarded to the COA for evaluation as required by existing rules and regulations;
c. The accounting unit should maintain complete and updated subsidiary ledgers for Receivables in accordance with Section 4(e) of the NGAS.
